{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/reference-lines-in-quicksight-9e09bd97910c", "time": 1683014205.599905, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/reference-lines-in-quicksight-9e09bd97910c/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Reference lines in QuickSight. Step by step process. | by Dr Sophie Acker | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Reference lines in QuickSight", "description": "The other day I was working on a dashboard in AWS QuickSight, creating a bar chart. As I opened the setting tab of my visual, I saw a new section: \u201creference line\u201d. I got really excited because I use\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "http://www.drsophieacker.com", "anchor_text": "www.drsophieacker.com", "paragraph_index": 22}], "all_paragraphs": ["The other day I was working on a dashboard in AWS QuickSight, creating a bar chart. As I opened the setting tab of my visual, I saw a new section: \u201creference line\u201d.", "I got really excited because I use to love reference lines on Tableau, so I gave it a go. You will find here a step by step process, as well as some thoughts on the limitations of the feature at this stage.", "I will be using the superstore dataset for all examples in this article.", "A reference line is a user-defined vertical or horizontal line in a graph. It is used to easily compare data points to that reference.", "For example, you could look at quarter to date sales, and have a reference line showing the quarterly target. You will be able to assess quickly whether you have passed the target yet or not.", "Another example could be, if you look at revenue across teams, to set a reference line as the average, so you would easily know which team is above/below average.", "The data used for the reference line can be a fixed number (eg: a target), or a calculated one (eg average, median, max, min\u2026).", "Reference lines are available for 3 visual types in QuickSight:", "Once you have created your chart, click on the \u201cFormat Visual\u201d icon on the top right corner of your chart, this will open the \u201cFormat Visual\u201d pane on the left hand side of the screen.", "The \u201cFormat Visual\u201d pane allows you to format title, X and Y axis and data labels. And now\u2026to create reference lines!", "Click on the reference line menu and then on \u201cadd new line\u201d to open to create a line.", "You are then prompted to chose the line settings.", "The first section covers the data you want to display: constant line or calculated line.", "Note you can add a calculated line based on a field that is not in your chart!", "The rest of the menu covers the line style (full, dotted or dashed, and color); and the label type, position, value format and font size.", "In the end, I ended up with such a bar chart. I have also formatted the axis and data labels along the way.", "First thing you will probably notice on the chart above, is that the automated positioning isn\u2019t great; the text and value are too close from the x axis. Not a huge deal but readability could be better.", "One way to solve for this is to use a vertical layout for this graph. I don\u2019t like to have to change my viz choice for reasons like that but hey \u2014 reads better. So up to you to decide what matters most in your use case.", "Then I tried to add a Parameter on the tab, to see if the average would recompute automatically. And it does! that\u2019s pretty cool.", "I think this feature is a great add to AWS QuickSight. I used to be a big fan of reference lines in Tableau, so I\u2019m glad to see the QuickSight team ramping up!", "Of course I would love to be able to color above or below the line, or create bands like in Tableau, but I am sure one day I will discover it is live in QuickSight. It is always full of surprises.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Dentist - Product Management - Business Intelligence. Brings disruptive technologies to market in dentistry. www.drsophieacker.com"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F9e09bd97910c&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Freference-lines-in-quicksight-9e09bd97910c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Freference-lines-in-quicksight-9e09bd97910c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Freference-lines-in-quicksight-9e09bd97910c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Freference-lines-in-quicksight-9e09bd97910c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/?source=post_page-----9e09bd97910c--------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/?source=post_page-----9e09bd97910c---------------------